  {/* 5 — ABOUT ROYS (expansion theme) */}
  <section class="py-16 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-6">What is this male Congo African Grey like to live with?</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Roys is a busy, confident male Congo African Grey who is happiest with a job to do and a household around him. If your home hums with activity, he is built for it. We have watched him grow from a clumsy chick into a young bird who treats an empty afternoon as a problem to solve, and he rewards an engaged family with a big, expressive personality.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Here at C.A.Gs we hand-raised Roys ourselves, in our Midland, Texas home, so what we tell you about him comes from feeding him every day rather than from a sales sheet. One thing we noticed early: he works a foraging toy methodically, twisting and testing a knot until it gives, then looking up to check whether anyone caught the win. That drive is the whole personality. Give him stimulation and company and he gives it straight back. Leave him with nothing to do and he will invent a project, usually a loud one.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 4 months he is curious about everything and still forming his sense of the world, which makes this a good moment for a family to shape his routine. Congo greys are famously bright — the species, <em>Psittacus erithacus</em>, sits among the most studied talking parrots in the world, and <a href="https://parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">the World Parrot Trust's grey parrot profile ↗</a> covers their cognition in depth. Roys puts that intelligence to work all day. He suits an active owner or household ready to keep an energetic bird busy and involved, not someone hoping for a quiet ornament on a perch.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">His first 30 days at home tend to follow a pattern we have seen across our greys. Week one he watches more than he plays, learning the rhythm of your house. By the second week he starts claiming a favorite perch and testing which sounds get a reaction. By the end of the month, in a home that shows up for him daily, he is asking to come out, leaning into head scratches on his terms, and beginning the soft babble that comes before real words. None of that happens on a schedule you can force — it happens because you are consistent.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Inside <a href="/african-grey-parrot-guide/" class="text-clay-text underline">our African Grey parrot guide</a> we cover what daily life with a Congo actually looks like, from foraging routines to the 40–60 year lifespan that makes one of these birds a genuine multi-decade commitment. If you are weighing whether a Congo or a Timneh fits your home, <a href="/congo-vs-timneh-african-grey/" class="text-clay-text underline">our Congo vs Timneh comparison</a> walks through the temperament and size differences side by side. Roys is firmly a Congo: bigger, redder-tailed, and in his case, full of beans.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">What we will not do is oversell him. He is a strong-willed young male who needs an owner with the time and patience to match his energy. Get that right and he is a remarkable companion. Get it wrong and a bored grey gets loud and frustrated. We would rather tell you that now than have you find out later.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* 6 — HEALTH & DOCUMENTATION (shared-fact, link-out-brief) */}
  <section class="py-16 px-4 bg-cream">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-6">What documentation comes with this male Congo African Grey for sale?</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">Every grey we sell ships with a full documentation set, and Roys is no exception. We never ask a buyer to take our word for it. He is captive-bred here in the USA, raised in a USDA Animal Welfare Act licensed aviary, and he goes home with the same paperwork standard we hold every C.A.Gs bird to:</p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-stone-600">
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span><span><strong>DNA-sexing certificate (♂)</strong> — lab-confirmed that Roys is male, so there is no guesswork.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span><span><strong>AAV health certificate</strong> — issued before he travels by a vet who follows <a href="https://aav.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Association of Avian Veterinarians standards ↗</a>.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span><span><strong>Hatch certificate + closed leg band</strong> — his traceable identity as a captive-bred bird.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span><span><strong>CITES captive-bred (Appendix I, USA) documentation</strong> — African Greys are CITES Appendix I, and captive-bred birds are legal to own and transfer domestically with the right paperwork, which Roys has.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span><span><strong>Weaning status</strong> — hand-reared and progressing on his own schedule toward independent feeding; he leaves us only once he is eating on his own.</span></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mt-6">Because the documents are the same across our nursery, <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/" class="text-clay-text underline">our CITES documentation page</a> explains what each one means in full, and <a href="/dna-tested-african-grey-for-sale/" class="text-clay-text underline">our DNA-tested greys</a> page covers why lab sexing matters before you commit. Roys is also covered by <a href="/african-grey-parrot-health-guarantee/" class="text-clay-text underline">our African Grey health guarantee</a>, which travels home with him alongside the documents.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* 7 — WHY ROYS (expansion theme) */}
  <section class="py-16 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-6">Why this male Congo African Grey might be right for you</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Roys suits a busy, engaged home that wants a confident grey in the middle of everything. An energetic young male like him adapts fast to a full house, takes to enrichment readily, and rewards an involved owner with personality in spades. At 4 months, you get decades of that energy ahead of you.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Picture the right fit. You are home often, or your household is. There are people around through the day — a family with older children who will help keep him stimulated, a couple who work from home, a retiree who wants a real companion rather than a quiet pet. You like the idea of a bird who greets the room, asks for your attention, and slowly builds a vocabulary tied to your daily life. That is the home Roys thrives in. Because we hand-raised him, we can tell you honestly how he responds to handling, to new faces, and to a high-activity household.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Now the honest other half, the part most listings skip. Roys is not the bird for a household that is empty ten hours a day, or for someone who wants a low-maintenance pet. A Congo grey needs daily interaction, mental work, and a person who treats the relationship as a long-term one. <a href="/african-grey-parrot-guide/" class="text-clay-text underline">What a Congo needs day to day</a> is real labor, joyful labor, but labor. <a href="https://www.avma.org/resources/pet-owners/petcare/selecting-pet-bird" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The American Veterinary Medical Association's pet-bird selection guidance ↗</a> is blunt about the lifelong commitment a parrot represents, and we agree with every word of it.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Then there is the lifespan. A healthy Congo African Grey can live 40 to 60 years. Roys could realistically still be greeting your kitchen decades from now, which means buying him is closer to taking on a family member than acquiring a pet. <a href="/african-grey-parrot-price/" class="text-clay-text underline">The lifetime commitment and true cost</a> deserve a clear look before you decide, and we would rather you sit with that math than rush it.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">So we screen, gently. We would rather Roys go to the home that genuinely fits him than to the first one to ask. If reading all this you are nodding along, picturing your living room with a bright, busy grey in it, that is the conversation we want to have with you.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* 8 — COUNTER-POSITIONING ($2,300 vs $850) (expansion theme) */}
  <section class="py-16 px-4 bg-cream">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-6">Why a real $2,300 Congo beats an $850 "bargain"</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A documented, hand-raised Congo African Grey cannot honestly be sold for $850. When you see that number, you are not looking at a cheaper version of Roys — you are looking at a bird missing the things that make Roys worth $2,300, or a listing that does not have a real bird behind it at all. The gap is not markup. It is paperwork, health, and accountability.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">Here is what the $850 price usually leaves out, point for point against what Roys comes with:</p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-stone-600 mb-6">
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-clay-text font-bold">✗</span><span><strong>Real:</strong> Roys ships with DNA, CITES, hatch certificate, and a closed leg band. <strong>Cheap:</strong> the $850 bird typically has no verifiable paperwork at all.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-clay-text font-bold">✗</span><span><strong>Real:</strong> lab DNA-sexing and an avian-vet (AAV) health check before travel. <strong>Cheap:</strong> no DNA sexing, no documented health exam.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-clay-text font-bold">✗</span><span><strong>Real:</strong> a USDA AWA licensed breeder you can verify and hold accountable after the sale. <strong>Cheap:</strong> a seller who vanishes once the deposit clears.</span></li>
      </ul>
      <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3">No verifiable paperwork (no DNA cert, no CITES, no hatch band)</h3>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Documentation is the first thing a bargain listing drops, because it costs the seller money and traceability they do not want. African Greys are CITES Appendix I, and a captive-bred bird is legal to own and transfer domestically only when the paperwork backs it up. A grey with no CITES record and no closed leg band is a grey you cannot prove anything about. Roys can be proven, on paper, top to bottom.</p>
      <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3">No DNA-sexing or avian-vet (AAV) health check</h3>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">An $850 listing almost never includes lab DNA-sexing or a pre-placement avian-vet exam, because both cost the breeder real money. That means you are guessing at the bird's sex and trusting a stranger on its health. With Roys, the DNA certificate settles his sex and the AAV health certificate documents his condition before he ever travels.</p>
      <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3">No breeder you can actually verify or hold accountable</h3>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The most expensive part of a cheap bird is the breeder you cannot find afterward. A real aviary answers the phone in year two. Knowing <a href="/how-to-avoid-african-grey-parrot-scams/" class="text-clay-text underline">how to avoid bird scams</a> mostly comes down to one habit: insist on documentation and a verifiable breeder, and walk away when either is missing. For the full picture of <a href="/african-grey-parrot-price/" class="text-clay-text underline">what a real grey actually costs</a>, the math behind $2,300 is open for you to read.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">None of this implies anything illegal about the cheap bird — only that you cannot verify it, and an unverifiable Appendix-I parrot is a risk you carry for 40 to 60 years. We think that is the worst place to save $1,450.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* 9 — PRICING & WHAT'S INCLUDED */}
  <section class="py-16 px-4">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-6">How much is this male Congo African Grey for sale, and what's included?</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-8">Roys is $2,300 with a $200 deposit to reserve him. That price covers a hand-raised, fully documented male Congo African Grey, not a bird plus a list of upsells. Here is the breakdown.</p>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3">Price &amp; reservation</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-3 text-stone-600 text-sm">
            <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-stone-200 pb-2"><span>Roys (male, 4 months)</span><strong class="text-logo-dark">$2,300</strong></li>
            <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-stone-200 pb-2"><span>Deposit to reserve</span><strong class="text-logo-dark">$200</strong></li>
            <li class="flex justify-between border-b border-stone-200 pb-2"><span>Airport Pickup (IATA, LAR)</span><strong class="text-logo-dark">$185</strong></li>
            <li class="flex justify-between"><span>Home Delivery (door-to-door)</span><strong class="text-logo-dark">$350</strong></li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-stone-500 text-xs mt-3">Ships nationwide &middot; $185 airport &middot; $350 home &middot; Delta / United / American</p>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm mt-3">A $200 deposit reserves Roys and pauses his listing for you, so you benefit from knowing no one else can claim him while you arrange the rest. The balance is due before he travels.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3">What's included</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-stone-600 text-sm">
            <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span> DNA sex certificate</li>
            <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span> Avian-vet (AAV) health certificate</li>
            <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span> Hatch certificate + closed leg band</li>
            <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span> CITES captive-bred documentation</li>
            <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span> Weaning &amp; feeding guidance</li>
            <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-green font-bold">✔</span> Health guarantee + post-arrival support</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm mt-3">Because everything that proves Roys is included, you are not chasing certificates after the fact. You get a settled, documented bird and a breeder who picks up the phone afterward.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mt-6">For how his price sits against the wider range, <a href="/african-grey-parrot-price/" class="text-clay-text underline">our full African Grey price breakdown</a> traces every figure. When you are ready, <a href="/contact-us/?bird=Roys" class="text-clay-text underline">our contact form</a> is the fastest way to reserve him.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* 10 — SHIPPING & LOGISTICS (expansion theme) */}
  <section class="py-16 px-4 bg-cream">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
      <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-3xl text-logo-dark mb-6">How does this male Congo African Grey for sale get to you safely?</h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Roys ships nationwide two ways, plus a premium third option. Airport Pickup is $185, where you collect him at your nearest major airport. Home Delivery is $350, door to door. An Avian Flight Nanny who carries him in-cabin is also available, quoted per route from about $750. Whatever you choose, he travels healthy, documented, and tracked.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">For the two standard tiers we book IATA-compliant live-animal cargo. Under the IATA Live Animals Regulations the booking carries the code <strong>LAR</strong>, and we fly the airlines with the strongest live-animal programs — <strong>Delta</strong>, <strong>United</strong>, and <strong>American</strong>. These are logistics choices, not locations: Roys can land at whichever major hub is closest to you, whether that is <strong>DEN</strong> in Denver, <strong>LAX</strong> in Los Angeles, <strong>MIA</strong> in Miami, or <strong>ORD</strong> in Chicago. We pick the route with the fewest connections and the kindest weather window.</p>
      <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3">What cargo day actually looks like</h3>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">On travel day Roys flies in an airline-approved, ventilated travel carrier sized for him, with bedding and a no-spill water source. We feed him before he leaves, label the carrier with his paperwork, and hand him to the airline's live-animal desk. You collect him at the destination cargo facility, usually within a couple of hours of landing, and his documents travel taped to the carrier so nothing gets separated from the bird. We send you the tracking and the flight details before he ever leaves Texas.</p>
      <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-xl text-logo-dark mb-3">When weather changes the plan</h3>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Airlines hold live animals to temperature limits, so during a heat wave or a hard freeze a flight can sit under embargo. When that happens we wait. We will reschedule Roys rather than push a bird onto a plane in conditions we would not accept for our own, and we keep you posted the whole time. The <strong>Avian Flight Nanny</strong> option exists for exactly these cases and for buyers who simply want a person holding the carrier the whole way — the nanny carries Roys in-cabin, so he never enters the cargo hold. Because that covers a chaperone's round-trip airfare, we quote it per route.</p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Tell us your nearest airport and a rough timeframe and we will lay out the cleanest option. <a href="/contact-us/?bird=Roys" class="text-clay-text underline">Reach out through our contact form</a> and we will map the route with you before you commit a dollar to travel.</p>
